# 3. Anomaly Detection Techniques

# 3.1 Statistical Anomaly Detection
print("\n--- Statistical Anomaly Detection ---")

# Function to detect statistical anomalies
def detect_statistical_anomalies(data, column, sigma=3):
    """Detect anomalies using mean and standard deviation."""
    mean = data[column].mean()
    std = data[column].std()
    lower_bound = mean - sigma * std
    upper_bound = mean + sigma * std
    
    anomalies = data[(data[column] < lower_bound) | (data[column] > upper_bound)]
    data[f'{column}_anomaly'] = ((data[column] < lower_bound) | (data[column] > upper_bound)).astype(int)
    
    print(f"Detected {len(anomalies)} anomalies in {column} using {sigma} sigma method")
    print(f"Anomaly percentage: {len(anomalies) / len(data) * 100:.2f}%")
    print(f"Threshold: {lower_bound:.2f} to {upper_bound:.2f}")
    
    return anomalies, data[f'{column}_anomaly']

# Apply statistical anomaly detection to key metrics
for metric in metrics:
    anomalies, _ = detect_statistical_anomalies(df, metric)
    
    # Visualize anomalies
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    plt.scatter(df.index, df[metric], s=1, label='Normal')
    plt.scatter(anomalies.index, anomalies[metric], color='red', s=10, label='Anomaly')
    plt.title(f'Statistical Anomalies in {metric.replace("_", " ").title()}')
    plt.xlabel('Data Point Index')
    plt.ylabel(metric)
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()

# Select features for anomaly detection

                   'server_temp_celsius', 'network_traffic_mbps', 'disk_iops']

# 3.2.1 Isolation Forest
print("\n-- Isolation Forest --")
iso_forest = IsolationForest(contamination=0.05, random_state=42)
df['iso_forest_anomaly'] = iso_forest.fit_predict(X_scaled)
df['iso_forest_anomaly'] = df['iso_forest_anomaly'].map({1: 0, -1: 1})  # Map predictions to 0 (normal) and 1 (anomaly)

print(f"Isolation Forest detected {df['iso_forest_anomaly'].sum()} anomalies")
print(f"Anomaly percentage: {df['iso_forest_anomaly'].mean() * 100:.2f}%")

# 3.2.2 Local Outlier Factor (LOF)
print("\n-- Local Outlier Factor --")
lof = LocalOutlierFactor(n_neighbors=20, contamination=0.05)
df['lof_anomaly'] = lof.fit_predict(X_scaled)
df['lof_anomaly'] = df['lof_anomaly'].map({1: 0, -1: 1})  # Map predictions to 0 (normal) and 1 (anomaly)

print(f"LOF detected {df['lof_anomaly'].sum()} anomalies")
print(f"Anomaly percentage: {df['lof_anomaly'].mean() * 100:.2f}%")

# 5. Time Series Anomaly Detection - Fixed version
print("\n--- Time Series Anomaly Detection ---")

# 5.1 Moving average based detection - with proper index alignment
# Let's use power consumption for time series analysis
power_ts = df.set_index('timestamp')['power_consumption_watts'].resample('1H').mean()

# Fill potential missing values
power_ts = power_ts.fillna(method='ffill')

# Calculate rolling statistics
window_size = 24  # 24 hours window
rolling_mean = power_ts.rolling(window=window_size).mean()
rolling_std = power_ts.rolling(window=window_size).std()

# Define bounds for anomaly detection
deviation_factor = 2
upper_bound = rolling_mean + deviation_factor * rolling_std
lower_bound = rolling_mean - deviation_factor * rolling_std

# Identify anomalies - making sure indices are aligned
# The key fix is to ensure ts_anomalies and power_ts have the same index
ts_anomalies = (power_ts > upper_bound) | (power_ts < lower_bound)

# Remove NaN values at the beginning due to the rolling window
# Make sure we keep the same index structure
valid_indices = ~rolling_mean.isna()
ts_anomalies = ts_anomalies & valid_indices

# Plot time series with bounds and anomalies
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 8))
plt.plot(power_ts, label='Power Consumption', alpha=0.5)
plt.plot(rolling_mean, label='Rolling Mean', color='green')
plt.plot(upper_bound, label='Upper Bound', color='red', linestyle='--')
plt.plot(lower_bound, label='Lower Bound', color='red', linestyle='--')

# Check if there are any anomalies and ensure index alignment
if ts_anomalies.sum() > 0:
    # This is the fixed line - we're using the boolean mask directly on power_ts
    anomaly_points = power_ts[ts_anomalies]
    plt.scatter(anomaly_points.index, anomaly_points, 
                color='red', label='Anomalies', s=50)

plt.title('Time Series Anomaly Detection - Power Consumption')
plt.xlabel('Time')
plt.ylabel('Power Consumption (Watts)')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

print(f"Detected {ts_anomalies.sum()} time series anomalies in power consumption")
print(f"Anomaly percentage: {ts_anomalies.mean() * 100:.2f}%")

# 5.2 Z-score method for multiple metrics - with proper index handling
time_metrics = ['power_consumption_watts', 'cpu_utilization', 'server_temp_celsius']
hourly_multimetric = df.set_index('timestamp')[time_metrics].resample('1H').mean().reset_index()

# Z-score calculation function
def calculate_zscore(df, metrics, window=24):
    """Calculate z-scores for each metric with proper handling of edge cases."""
    df_zscore = df.copy()
    
    for metric in metrics:
        # Handle edge cases for rolling calculations
        rolling_mean = df[metric].rolling(window=window, min_periods=1).mean()
        rolling_std = df[metric].rolling(window=window, min_periods=1).std()
        
        # Handle potential zero std
        rolling_std = rolling_std.replace(0, np.nan)
        rolling_std = rolling_std.fillna(df[metric].std() if df[metric].std() > 0 else 1.0)
        
        df_zscore[f'{metric}_zscore'] = (df[metric] - rolling_mean) / rolling_std
    
    return df_zscore

# Calculate z-scores
hourly_zscore = calculate_zscore(hourly_multimetric, time_metrics)

# Flag anomalies based on z-score threshold
zscore_threshold = 3
for metric in time_metrics:
    hourly_zscore[f'{metric}_anomaly'] = (abs(hourly_zscore[f'{metric}_zscore']) > zscore_threshold).astype(int)

# Visualize z-score anomalies
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
for i, metric in enumerate(time_metrics, 1):
    plt.subplot(len(time_metrics), 1, i)
    plt.plot(hourly_zscore['timestamp'], hourly_zscore[f'{metric}_zscore'], label='Z-score')
    plt.axhline(y=zscore_threshold, color='r', linestyle='--', label='Threshold')
    plt.axhline(y=-zscore_threshold, color='r', linestyle='--')
    
    # Plot anomalies - with proper filtering
    anomalies = hourly_zscore[hourly_zscore[f'{metric}_anomaly'] == 1]
    if len(anomalies) > 0:
        plt.scatter(anomalies['timestamp'], anomalies[f'{metric}_zscore'], 
                   color='red', label='Anomalies', s=50)
    
    plt.title(f'Z-score Anomalies in {metric.replace("_", " ").title()}')
    plt.xlabel('Time')
    plt.ylabel('Z-score')
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# 6. Predictive Maintenance

# 6.1 Fault Prediction Model
if 'has_fault' in df.columns and df['has_fault'].sum() > 0:
    print("\n--- Fault Prediction Model ---")
    
    from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
    from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split, cross_val_score
    from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score, roc_auc_score
    
    # Prepare features for fault prediction
    fault_features = ['cpu_utilization', 'memory_utilization', 'power_consumption_watts', 
                     'server_temp_celsius', 'network_traffic_mbps', 'disk_iops']
    
    # Add derived features
    df['power_per_cpu'] = df['power_consumption_watts'] / np.maximum(df['cpu_utilization'], 0.01)  # Avoid division by zero
    df['temp_per_cpu'] = df['server_temp_celsius'] / np.maximum(df['cpu_utilization'], 0.01)
    
    fault_features += ['power_per_cpu', 'temp_per_cpu']
    
    # Add time-based features
    fault_features += ['hour', 'day_of_week', 'is_weekend']
    
    # Add anomaly scores
    fault_features += ['combined_anomaly_score']
    
    # Define X and y
    X = df[fault_features]
    y = df['has_fault']
    
    # Handle categorical features
    if 'server_type' in df.columns:
        X = pd.get_dummies(df[fault_features + ['server_type']], columns=['server_type'])
    
    # Split data
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42, stratify=y)
    
    # Scale features
    scaler = StandardScaler()
    X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
    X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)
    
    # Train model
    rf_clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42, class_weight='balanced')
    rf_clf.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
    
    # Evaluate model
    y_pred = rf_clf.predict(X_test_scaled)
    y_proba = rf_clf.predict_proba(X_test_scaled)[:, 1]
    
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred)
    recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred)
    f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred)
    roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_proba)
    
    print("Fault Prediction Model Performance:")
    print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")
    print(f"Precision: {precision:.4f}")
    print(f"Recall: {recall:.4f}")
    print(f"F1 Score: {f1:.4f}")
    print(f"ROC AUC: {roc_auc:.4f}")
    
    # Feature importance
    feature_importance = pd.DataFrame({
        'feature': X_train.columns,
        'importance': rf_clf.feature_importances_
    }).sort_values('importance', ascending=False)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
    sns.barplot(x='importance', y='feature', data=feature_importance.head(15))
    plt.title('Feature Importance for Fault Prediction')
    plt.xlabel('Importance')
    plt.ylabel('Feature')
    plt.grid(True, axis='x')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    
    print("\nTop 10 features for fault prediction:")
    print(feature_importance.head(10))
    
    # Confusion Matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues', 
               xticklabels=['No Fault', 'Fault'], yticklabels=['No Fault', 'Fault'])
    plt.title('Confusion Matrix: Fault Prediction')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.ylabel('Actual')
    plt.show()
    
    # Print classification report
    print("\nClassification Report:")
    print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

# 7.2 Anomaly clusters
if len(anomalies_df) > 0:
    # Cluster anomalies to identify patterns
    anomaly_features_for_clustering = ['cpu_utilization', 'memory_utilization', 
                                      'power_consumption_watts', 'server_temp_celsius']
    
    # Scale features
    anomaly_X = anomalies_df[anomaly_features_for_clustering]
    anomaly_scaler = StandardScaler()
    anomaly_X_scaled = anomaly_scaler.fit_transform(anomaly_X)
    
    # Use KMeans for clustering
    from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
    
    # Determine optimal number of clusters using elbow method
    inertia = []
    for k in range(1, min(10, len(anomaly_X_scaled))):
        kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42)
        kmeans.fit(anomaly_X_scaled)
        inertia.append(kmeans.inertia_)
    
    # Plot elbow curve
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.plot(range(1, min(10, len(anomaly_X_scaled))), inertia, marker='o')
    plt.title('Elbow Method for Optimal k')
    plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')
    plt.ylabel('Inertia')
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()
    
    # Choose k based on elbow method (simplify to k=3 for demonstration)
    k = min(3, len(anomaly_X_scaled))
    
    # Apply KMeans
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42)
    anomalies_df['cluster'] = kmeans.fit_predict(anomaly_X_scaled)
    
    # Analyze clusters
    cluster_analysis = anomalies_df.groupby('cluster')[anomaly_features_for_clustering].mean()
    print("\nAnomaly Cluster Analysis:")
    print(cluster_analysis)
    
    # Visualize clusters
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 10))
    for i, metric in enumerate(anomaly_features_for_clustering, 1):
        plt.subplot(2, 2, i)
        sns.boxplot(x='cluster', y=metric, data=anomalies_df)
        plt.title(f'{metric.replace("_", " ").title()} by Cluster')
        plt.xlabel('Cluster')
        plt.ylabel(metric)
        plt.grid(True, axis='y')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    
    

# 8. Recommendations and Reporting

# 8.1 Summarize key findings
print("\n1. Key Findings:")

# Overall anomaly rate
print(f" Overall anomaly rate: {df['is_anomaly'].mean() * 100:.2f}%")

# Most common anomaly metrics (those with highest contribution to anomaly detection)
anomaly_contribution = {}
for col in [c for c in df.columns if c.endswith('_anomaly') and c != 'is_anomaly']:
    anomaly_contribution[col] = df[col].sum() / df['is_anomaly'].sum() * 100

# Sort and print top contributors    
anomaly_sorted = sorted(anomaly_contribution.items(), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)
print(" Metrics most frequently flagged as anomalous:")
for metric, percentage in anomaly_sorted[:3]:
    clean_name = metric.replace('_anomaly', '').replace('_', ' ').title()
    print(f"  - {clean_name}: {percentage:.1f}% of anomalies")

# Time patterns
if 'hour' in df.columns:
    anomaly_hour_rate = df.groupby('hour')['is_anomaly'].mean() * 100
    worst_hour = anomaly_hour_rate.idxmax()
    worst_rate = anomaly_hour_rate.max()
    print(f" Highest anomaly rate occurs at {worst_hour}:00 hours ({worst_rate:.1f}%)")

if 'day_of_week' in df.columns:
    weekday_map = {0: 'Monday', 1: 'Tuesday', 2: 'Wednesday', 
                  3: 'Thursday', 4: 'Friday', 5: 'Saturday', 6: 'Sunday'}
    anomaly_day_rate = df.groupby('day_of_week')['is_anomaly'].mean() * 100
    worst_day_idx = anomaly_day_rate.idxmax()
    worst_day = weekday_map[worst_day_idx]
    worst_day_rate = anomaly_day_rate.max()
    print(f" Highest anomaly rate occurs on {worst_day}s ({worst_day_rate:.1f}%)")

# Server type patterns
if 'server_type' in df.columns:
    server_anomaly_rate = df.groupby('server_type')['is_anomaly'].mean() * 100
    worst_server = server_anomaly_rate.idxmax()
    worst_server_rate = server_anomaly_rate.max()
    print(f" Server type '{worst_server}' has the highest anomaly rate ({worst_server_rate:.1f}%)")

# If we have fault data, report on detection success
if 'has_fault' in df.columns:
    true_positives = ((df['is_anomaly'] == 1) & (df['has_fault'] == 1)).sum()
    all_faults = df['has_fault'].sum()
    fault_detection_rate = true_positives / all_faults * 100 if all_faults > 0 else 0
    print(f" Anomaly detection identified {fault_detection_rate:.1f}% of actual faults")
    
    # Most detectable fault types
    if 'fault_type' in df.columns:
        fault_detect_rate = []
        for fault in df['fault_type'].unique():
            if fault == 'none' or pd.isna(fault):
                continue
            fault_df = df[df['fault_type'] == fault]
            if len(fault_df) == 0:
                continue
            detected = (fault_df['is_anomaly'] == 1).sum()
            total = len(fault_df)
            rate = detected / total * 100
            fault_detect_rate.append((fault, rate))
        
        if fault_detect_rate:
            fault_detect_rate.sort(key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)
            best_fault, best_rate = fault_detect_rate[0]
            worst_fault, worst_rate = fault_detect_rate[-1]
            print(f" Most detectable fault: '{best_fault}' ({best_rate:.1f}%)")
            print(f" Least detectable fault: '{worst_fault}' ({worst_rate:.1f}%)")

        server_metrics = {}
        for metric in anomaly_features:

            avg_normal = df[(df['server_type'] == worst_server) & (df['is_anomaly'] == 0)][metric].mean()
            diff_percent = ((avg_anomaly - avg_normal) / avg_normal) * 100 if avg_normal != 0 else float('inf')
            server_metrics[metric] = abs(diff_percent)
        
        # Top distinctive metrics
